	affiliations = {School of Computer Science and Engineering, Hunan University of Science and Technology, Hunan, 411201, China},
	abstract = {With the explosive growth of online content, content moderation has become a critical component of platform governance. This paper presents a systematic and comprehensive review of Large Language Model (LLM)-based content moderation methods, research progress, and future prospects. Traditional content moderation approaches, primarily relying on keyword matching, rule-based systems, and conventional deep learning models, while effective in specific scenarios, face significant challenges in nuanced contextual understanding, adapting to novel and evolving violation tactics, and ensuring equitable cross-lingual application. LLMs, with their powerful semantic understanding, contextual reasoning, and generative capabilities, introduce a transformative paradigm for content moderation. This paper first analyzes the technical characteristics and inherent limitations of traditional moderation methods. It then delves into the application architecture, key enabling technologies, and innovative applications of LLM-based approaches, highlighting how LLMs can enhance moderation accuracy, enable the screening of complex and subtle cases, provide high-quality decision explanations, augment human reviewers, and facilitate user participation in governance processes. However, the deployment of LLMs in content moderation is not without its challenges, including concerns related to model bias, linguistic inequality, the potential for algorithmic monoculture, and overarching legitimacy and ethical considerations. This paper proposes a multidimensional evaluation framework that extends beyond mere accuracy, emphasizing accuracy, speed, and transparency for straightforward cases, while prioritizing decision explanation, procedural justice, and fairness for complex and sensitive cases. Finally, future research directions are outlined, focusing on mitigating model bias, enhancing cross-lingual and cross-cultural capabilities, improving the explainability and robustness of LLM-based systems, and developing more inclusive, transparent, and community-led content moderation ecosystems. This review aims to provide a foundational understanding for researchers and practitioners, fostering the development of more effective, equitable, and responsible content moderation solutions in the era of advanced AI. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.},
