	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105014235054?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Striks Faculty of Law, College of Management, Israel},
	abstract = {Copyright law can gain much by implementing administrative law principles into its enforcement systems. In the age of massive online traffic of copyrighted content, copyright law stands at the heart of public discourse and involves public policy considerations more than ever. Online copyright enforcement is inevitably conducted by computerized systems that can handle large amounts of uploaded content. These automated enforcement systems raise questions about whether basic principles of procedural fairness, as perceived in democratic societies, are guaranteed. This discourse is significantly urgent because of the requirement obligating online platforms to deploy automated copyright enforcement systems, adopted in Article 17 to the EU Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market. Applying administrative law procedures reflecting some core procedural justice principles may contribute significantly to democratizing copyright enforcement systems. Three main principles discussed in the present article are: (a) giving reasons for decisions made; (b) setting objective review mechanisms; and (c) public participation in rule-making. A process of democratization may serve both users in protecting their fundamental rights and copyright owners, who would gain legitimacy and greater public support for protecting their economic interests. Thus, the introduction of administrative law principles into copyright law may serve the public good well in its broadest meaning. © The Editor and Contributors Severally 2025. All rights reserved.},
	author_keywords = {Copyright democratization; Copyright enforcement; Online procedural justice},
	keywords = {Copyrights; Information systems; Information use; Law enforcement; Public policy; Administrative law; Automated enforcement; Computerized systems; Copyright democratization; Copyright enforcement; Copyright law; Large amounts; On-line traffic; Online procedural justice; Procedural justice; Online systems},
