	title = {A theory of the infrastructure-level bureaucracy: Understanding the consequences of data-exchange for procedural justice, organizational decision-making, and data itself},
	year = {2025},
	journal = {Government Information Quarterly},
	volume = {42},
	number = {2},
	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1016/j.giq.2025.102021},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105000148843?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Kafkabrigade Foundation, Bilderdijkstraat 79N, 1053 KM, Amsterdam, Netherlands; Tilburg University, Tilburg Law School, Montesquieu Building Room M 924. Professor Cobbenhagenlaan, Tilburg, 221 5037 DE, Netherlands; Centro de Investigación y Docencia Económicas (CIDE), Carretera México-Toluca 3655, Colonia Lomas de Santa Fe, Ciudad de México, C.P. 01210, Mexico},
	abstract = {The interconnectedness of government organizations through data-exchange is proliferating. This is relevant for many debates in public administration today since all applications of data-driven government rest on a foundation of data. In this article, rather than focusing on specific applications, we analyze the way supra-organizational data-exchange shapes such applications and specifically automated administrative decision-making (AADM). We argue that the whole of bureaucracy that is connected through data-exchange implies the organizational separation of the collection or gathering of government data from the exchange, modification, combination and/or analysis and subsequently its (re)use in decision-making processes. To analyze the consequences of this new division of labor we further develop the concept of the infrastructure-level bureaucracy and formulate hypotheses on its consequences for data itself, organizations, and citizens. Ultimately, we argue infrastructural information flows pose challenges for democratic control and for procedural lawfulness in the constitutional state. © 2025 The Authors},
